2022 MASH UP. 
The year has come to a close. I think I took my career to a whole new level this year as I gained the confidence to complete most of the jobs that were thrown my way. I learned and tested a lot of new techniques, gear, powersaws, etc. I gained a lot of new friends in the industry, advice and possible future opportunities. I also got a bit too comfortable and picked up some bad habits so I appreciate being called out on it and will work on minimizing those. Thank you everyone for continuing to follow along and cheers to another great year!

SURGICAL 🔪.. Different styles of cuts used for a desired outcome. Experience pays off. A lot of methods in treework just cannot be taught, they must be experienced. All trees react differently. Here i have chosen many different styles off the top of my head in a matter of seconds to allow the branches to drop, swing, and land exactly where I want them and where they will be easiest for the ground crew to deal with. Not all of the cuts on this tree went exactly how I pictured but thats whats great about an environment like this where there isnt much to avoid. I know a lot of guys who probably would have just slammed this tree down without rigging at all, then leave it up to the groundcrew to deal with. Thats not how we roll. Work hard for your team and they will work hard for you!

Rigging Redirects 🌲🪚🪓🪢
Whether it be natural crotch or using pulleys, carabiners, etc., can be very useful for debris management, job efficiency, and climber safety. In this clip I show several ways I set my rigging line to keep the job moving smoothly, while keeping the limbs swinging away from me while also having the ability to retrieve the rope quite quickly and easily for the next setup. These setups often require on the spot planning as more often than not, the plan changes once you are in the tree. Be aware of how many redirects you add for your size of cuts as each redirect adds friction, especially with natural crotch rigging. That being said, adding friction can be a good thing as it can eliminate the need for friction management devices in a situation and keep things simple. I often like to practice with limited gear to prepare for situations when I dont have the gadgets I think I may need. Climb safe and have fun. Keep the brain working!
